    <div xml:id="PN247">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>yāṉai tanta muḷimara viṟakiṟ</l>
<l>kāṉavar pottiya ñelitī viḷakkattu</l>
<l>maṭamāṉ perunirai vaikutuyi leṭuppi</l>
<l>manti cīkku maṇaṅkuṭai muṉṟili</l>
<l>ṉīrvār kūnta lirumpuṟan tāḻap</l>
<l>pērañar kaṇṇaḷ peruṅkāṭu nōkkit</l>
<l>terumaru mamma tāṉētaṉ koḻunaṉ</l>
<l>muḻavukaṇ ṭuyilāk kaṭiyuṭai viyaṉakarc</l>
<l>ciṟunaṉi tamiya ḷāyiṉu</l>
<l>miṉṉuyir naṭuṅkunta ṉiḷamaipuṟaṅ koṭuttē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In [the light of] the lamp that is a fire rubbed by the forest people (2)</l>
<l>on firewood from a dry tree brought by an elephant, (1)</l>
<l>in the fearful front-yard scratched up by female monkeys, (4)</l>
<l>arousing from the sleep they stayed in a large herd of innocent deer, (3)</l>
<l>while [her] water-flowing tresses hang down [her] back, (5)</l>
<l>she whose eyes [hold] great grief looks at the great forest (6)</l>
<l>[and] is unnerved, alas. (6a-c)</l>
<l>Although she was very lonely, a little, (9)</l>
<l>in the protected vast mansion of her husband where the eye of the drum does not sleep (7d-8)</l>
<l>[her] precious life trembles when turning [her] back upon [her] youth. (10)</l>
</lg>

    </div>
